Demonstration of Data Mining Techniques on Education Data

Alex Dragonetti

2024-08-04

1 Overview

The following is meant to be a demonstration of Data cleaning, preparation, Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA), and various statistical techniques, as well as their possible applications with School District data.

All data used for this project was collected from the School District of Philadelphia’s District Performance Office. The data used below, and their descriptions, were found on their website: https://www.philasd.org/performance/.

1.1 Introduction to the Data

We felt it was important, for demonstration purposes, to include data related to both school attributes and school performance. The datasets that we are beginning with are:

*College Matriculation - Students are considered to have matriculated if they enrolled at a postsecondary institution that reports information to the National Student Clearinghouse (NSC).

*Graduation - Contains data on the graduation rate of ninth grade cohorts (ie, the ninth grade cohort of SY 2019-2020 would generally be eligible for graduating at the end of SY 2022-2023).

*Average Daily Attendance - Contains daily attendance at 3 different reporting times throughout SY 22-23. It does not specify time of year in the dataset or description. Since this is only meant to be a demonstration of techniques, these values will be averaged, and each school’s average will be included in further analysis.

*90% Attendance - This dataset contains the number and percentage of enrolled students in each grade that attended at least 90% of instructional days. While the data contains breakdowns of different student groups, we will only use data for all students in our larger analysis.

*Food Insecurity - Contains school-level information about household food insecurity status. This information is based on responses to questions about food insecurity that appear on the parent/guardian Philly School Experience Survey (PSES). Only schools that met the minimum response rate threshold for the parent/guardian survey are included.

2 Initial EDA and Preparing the Data

2.1 Original Data

2.1.1 Food Security Rate Data

First, we will look at the food security data. We expect this dataset to have the most missing values, as a school’s values are only included if it met a response criterion (while not stated on the District’s website, we believe the criterion is 10% or more eligible households respond). We will also format the ULCS.Code variable name to align with other datasets.

Notably, this dataset contains a different formatting for the School.Name variable: this dataset calls school number 1010 “Bartram, John High School”, compared to the other datasets’ “John Bartram High School”. While this is understandable, as many district schools named after a person are referred to by the last name only, It is our recommendation to adopt a more uniform formatting for school names. While removing school names from this dataset will lead to missing values in our full dataset, schools can be identified by ULCS.Code as well.

colnames(df.food)[1]<-"ULCS.Code"

df.col<-df.col[,-3]

ggplot(df.col, aes(x=Number.of.Graduates, y=First.Fall.Matriculation.Rate))+
  geom_point()

While we were not looking for a pattern, this gives us a good idea of the average size of each school’s graduating class, showing us that schools of varying sizes will be represented by our analyses.

2.1.3 Attendance Data

We have two datasets related to attendance: one with schools’ attendance rate, and one with the number and percent of students with 90% daily attendance or higher. As stated in the introduction, the daily attendance values will be averaged, and each school’s average will be included in further analysis.

We will also create a subset of the 90% dataset that only has total school data. In doing so, we will eliminate redundant variables (there is no need to specify school year, group, etc, since the output data is all one school year and one type of data).

Similar to our matriculation dataset, we will need to change character variables Attendance.90.N and Attendance.90.Rate to numeric for later analysis.

The stark difference in graduation rate is surprising at first and may warrant further investigation. First, a quick check on the number of each being represented:

table(df.g2$Sector)
## 
## Alternative    District 
##          26          55

While there are many Alternative schools represented in the data, a smaller amount, with presumably smaller class sizes (evidenced by mean graduation value of 13 students compared to District schools’ 126) would suggest smaller sample sizes make this specific category more susceptible to influence from extreme outliers.

Also of note, Alternative schools (such as those found in the district’s Opportunity Network) are often for at-risk students, which generally see lower rates of graduation. Their role for putting students ‘back on track’, as the district puts it, can not be undervalued and we will not attempt to draw any major conclusions about their performance, relative to the rest of the district.

2.2 Combining Data sets

While conducting our EDA, we have been making reduced data sets that have data for entire school populations, and only for the 22-23 school year. We have also ensured uniform formatting for variable names (like changing school code to UCLS.Code to match other datasets) and ensured that variables are working as desired (like eliminating the % so a variable can function as numeric).

Note that this could be done differently to focus on any specific subset of district population, however, this project is for demonstration purposes, so we will use the most general data that we have access to.

While doing this, we noticed that the variable Sector has its information split across two different datasets - some schools only having their value in one dataset, some in another, some in both - so we import both as separate variables, then coalesce them into one with the dplyr package.

data_frames<-list(df.a, df.ada2, df.col, df.g2, df.food)

df.full<- Reduce(function(x, y) merge(x, y, by = c("ULCS.Code"), all = TRUE), data_frames)

df.full <- df.full %>%
  mutate(Sector = coalesce(Sector.x, Sector.y)) %>%
  select(-Sector.x, -Sector.y) %>%
  mutate(School.Name = coalesce(School.Name.x, School.Name.y)) %>%
  select(-School.Name.x, -School.Name.y)
  
df.full<-df.full[,-6]
colnames(df.full)[11]<-"Learning.Network"
df.full$ULCS.Code<-as.character(df.full$ULCS.Code)

4 Imputing Missing Values

While we have no shortage of data, we are missing many responses to the food security survey. We saw earlier that a value of High or marginal food security rate was highly correlated with many variables of interest. We will explore imputing values of that rate based on existing data.

4.1 Finding Variables to use Imputing

Luckily, our dataset includes a variable states whether a school met the reporting criteria. We use this to see whether schools who met the reporting threshold are similar to schools that did not - if they are similar, it may indicate that they could be used as predictors for imputing.

First, the initial boxplots:

boxplot(Total.Students ~ `Met Reporting Threshold`, data=df.full)

boxplot(Attendance.90.Rate ~ `Met Reporting Threshold`, data=df.full)

boxplot(Mean.Attendance ~ `Met Reporting Threshold`, data=df.full)

Since all three variables have similar distributions, we will make an initial model that uses all 3 as predictor variables.

4.2 Creating a testing set

For ease of programming, we will make a separate dataset for testing and predicting by filtering observations that have or have not met reporting criteria.

To make sure that we have values in each of the variables, we will only consider observations with values in all desired variables for our model building - the alternative returns errors.

df.test<-filter(df.full, `Met Reporting Threshold`=="Yes")
df.pred<-filter(df.full, `Met Reporting Threshold`=="No")

test.fi.columns <- c("Total.Students", "Attendance.90.Rate", "Mean.Attendance", "Learning.Network", "High or marginal food security rate")

df.test2 <- na.omit(df.test[, test.fi.columns])

Use of the summary function shows that we have 166 observations in our test group and 100 observations looking for predictions.

4.3 Testing and Choosing a Model

We will create and judge multiple models below.

4.3.1 Linear Regression

A linear regression models the linear relationship between an explanatory variable (or variables) and a response variable. This model is a good predictor when there is reason to believe that a linear relationship exists.

set.seed(215)
fitControl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)

colnames(df.test2)[5]<-"y"

model.f.lm <- train(y ~ Attendance.90.Rate + Mean.Attendance + Learning.Network + Total.Students, 
                  data = df.test2, 
                  method = "lm",
                  trControl = fitControl)

## 
## Tuning parameter 'intercept' was held constant at a value of TRUE

Our output has two statistics we will compare to the other model, RMSE and Rsquared. The Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) of a model is a measure of error. Ideally, our model has the lowest RMSE possible. It is calculated with the following equation:

\(RMSE=\sqrt{\Sigma_{i=1}^n (\hat{y}-y{i}^2)/n }\)

The Rsquared is a measure of correlation. It can range from values of -1 to 1. -1 is a perfect negative relationship, 1 is a perfect positive relation, 0 is no relationship. We would like our Rsquared value to be close to 1.

We will use these two metrics to compare to our models.

4.3.2 K-Nearest Neighbors

K-Nearest Neighbors is a non-parametric modeling technique. It is a more flexible model than linear regression, because it does not assume a relationship to be linear. Instead, it selects a value of \(K\), then finds an observation’s \(k\) nearest neighbors (closest Euclidean distances), and averages those \(k\) values of \(Y\) for a predicted value.

Since this model uses Euclidean distance, we will scale our variables, meaning the variable Learning.Network will be omitted.

set.seed(215)
df.test.sc<-scale(df.test2[sapply(df.test2, is.numeric)])

kGrid <- expand.grid(k = seq(1, 9, by = 2))

model.f.knn <- train(y ~ Attendance.90.Rate + Mean.Attendance + Total.Students,
                  data = df.test.sc, 
                  method = "knn",
                  tuneGrid=kGrid,
                  trControl = fitControl)

4.3.3 Random Forest

A Random Forest model is an ensemble model that creates multiple uncorrelated decision trees and arrives at a final value by averaging their results. The difference between it an bagging is the number of explanatory variables considered at each split of the tree - a random forest will consider fewer, chosen at random, meaning more variables are likely to be considered at each tree.

set.seed(215)

mtryGrid <- expand.grid(mtry = 2:4)
model.f.rf <- train(y ~ Attendance.90.Rate + Mean.Attendance + Learning.Network + Total.Students, 
                  data = df.test2, 
                  method = "rf",
                  tuneGrid=mtryGrid,
                  trControl = fitControl)

5 Unsupervised Learning

5.1 Overview

Unsupervised learning is used when there is no \(Y\) variable, meaning, we are not looking for a relationship between a group of explanatory variables and a response variable of interest. We can use various unsupervised learning techniques to conduct analyses like examining relationships between variables or putting observations into clusters based on certain characteristics.

5.2 Clustering

Clustering is a statistical technique that makes subgroups (called clusters) out of observations. This technique can help us identify groups

5.2.1 Preparing and Scaling the Data

Clustering can depend heavily on each variable’s units of measurement. To account for this, we will first scale our dataset. We will also remove redundant variables that are inherently correlated with one another. For example, instead of including the raw number of graduates and graduation rate, we will just include the rate.

Since our clustering function requires non-missing values, we will attempt to remove variables with many missing values - we don’t want to reduce our sample size by too much! This means we will have to drop food security scores for now, as too many are missing and we have no viable way to impute them.

We will also cluster high schools and non-high schools (referred to as elementary for simplicity) because high schools have more variables related to them - graduation and college matriculation stats do not exist for elementary schools - and we want to use information when we can.

df.hs <- df.full[,-c(12:21)] %>% filter(!is.na(Grad.Cohort.N))%>% na.omit

df.elem <- df.full[,-c(12:21)] %>% filter(is.na(Grad.Cohort.N))

df.elem<-df.elem[,-c(6:10)]%>%na.omit


df.hs.sc<-scale(df.hs[sapply(df.hs, is.numeric)])

df.el.sc<-scale(df.elem[sapply(df.elem, is.numeric)])

5.2.2 K-Means

K-Means is an algorithm that partitions observations. This means that each observation will fall in one - and only one - cluster. It measures this with Euclidean Distances, a numerical value that generally warrants using scaled data.

To find a point of diminishing returns, we will use a scree plot and look for an ‘elbow’ - a point where the reduction of variance hits a low plateau. We will test around k=13 clusters, the existing number of Neighborhood Networks in the School District of Philadelphia (not counting Acceleration, Opportunity, Charter, or Innovation Schools)

set.seed(215)

Supervised learning is used to examine relationships between explanatory variable(s) and a response variable. We can use supervised learning techniques to look for and measure associations between those variables.

We will look at two response variables, Graduation Rate and College Matriculation Rate. For each response variable, we will fit two different models and compare them. We will use different models for the sake of demonstrating multiple statistical techniques, but in practice, we could also find that the same model type could be the best for both variables.

We will fit models both with and without statistics related to food insecurity to see if these are good predictors. While we believe that they could be, requiring them for our model effectively cuts our sample in half.

6.2.1 Bootstrap Aggregation

Bootstrap Aggregating (or Bagging) is an ensemble model - meaning multiple models are considered in making a final prediction - that applies a sampling technique called bootstrapping to a model (in this case decision tree model) to reduce variance.

A benefit of bagging is we can see importance of variables in coming up with the regression value, meaning, if we want to see a change in \(Y\), we can see which variable had a higher importance in determining its’ value and target it with future interventions.

set.seed(215)

mtryGrid <- expand.grid(mtry = 5)

model.bag.1 <- train(First.Fall.Matriculation.Rate ~ Grad.Rate + Attendance.90.Rate + Mean.Attendance + Learning.Network + `High or marginal food security rate`, 
                  data = df.mat.rate1, 
                  method = "rf",
                  tuneGrid=mtryGrid,
                  trControl = fitControl)

6.2.3 Discussion: College Matriculation Rate

We attempted to fit two different types of models to College Matriculation rate: a Bagging model and a Random Forest model. We also attempted to evaluate the efficacy of High or Marginal Food Security rate as a predictor of college matriculation. We found that a Random Forest model with m=2 was the superior model, and that, in our initial findings, food security rating does not appear necessary to make the ‘optimal’ predictor.

We would like to caution against definitively stating that it is not a valuable predictor and will elaborate in our conclusion.

Of note, learning Network 1 is a strong predictor for college matriculation, but not graduation. As the current network structure has schools in the same network spread across the city, it is hard to get the demographics for a single network. Further analysis would have been recommended to see if network designation is functionally a stand-in for an economic demographic, but the district is planning on changing their Learning Network boundaries ahead of SY 2024-25, so any analysis of soon-to-be outdated Learning Networks would likely be moot.

7 Conclusion

7.1 General Observations and Recommendations

The School District of Philadelphia’s collection and sharing of data is admirable and impressive. The existing infrastructure is more than enough to generate many data-based solutions, initiatives, etc. We would recommend a uniform practice for data formatting. In just 5 base datasets, we can see various formatting for the same variable names (UCLS.Code vs schoolid_ucls), character variables (John Bartram High School vs Bartram, John High School), numeric variables (percentages in number form vs percentages with a “%” at the end, making them character variables), and how missing values are kept (blank vs “s” or “S”). While it would be time-consuming, a standardized approach to all of this would make working with data much easier and could save time overall.

7.2 Recommendations Based on Supervised Learning

We would like to caution that our supervised learning was conducted with a small subset of the data, as the response variables we used only applied to high schools (graduation and college matriculation rate).

Based on our findings, it is our belief that a high attendance is paramount to student - and subsequently school - success in the both graduation and college matriculation metrics. We feel that the district is right to make regular student attendance a high priority. While it is likely very difficult, we would also recommend attempting to collect data on students post-high school paths that do not include college. While college matriculation is likely the easiest to record, knowledge of student placement in other ‘successful’ paths - apprenticeships, jobs, etc - could be a valuable student success metric as college enrollment continues a decade-plus of decline.

We also believe that a school’s food security rating may prove to be a useful predictor of graduation rate. We would recommend checking available data from previous school years (especially prior to the COVID-19 pandemic) using methods similar to the ones demonstrated in this report.
